# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: hcl-config
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:hcl-config/configuration-file] A **configuration file**, also known as **config file**, is a file that stores data used to configure a software system such as an application, a server or an operating system.
[src:hcl-config/configuration-file] Some applications provide a tool to create, modify, and verify the syntax of their configuration files – sometimes via graphical user interface (GUI).
[src:hcl-config/configuration-file] For context, system administrators may be expected to create and modify text config files via a text editor.
[src:hcl-config/configuration-file] For server processes and operating-system settings, there is often no standard tool, but operating systems may provide graphical interfaces such as YaST or debconf.
[src:hcl-config/configuration-file] Some computer programs only read their configuration files at startup.
[src:hcl-config/configuration-file] Others periodically check the configuration files for changes.
[src:hcl-config/configuration-file] Users can instruct some programs to re-read the configuration files and apply the changes to the current process, or indeed to read arbitrary files as a configuration file.
[src:hcl-config/configuration-file] There are no definitive standards or strong conventions.
[src:hcl-config/configuration-file] In general, a config file can have any format.
[src:hcl-config/configuration-file] The format that applies to a particular system is determined by the design of that system.
[src:hcl-config/configuration-file] Often, a standardized format is used since it allows for using tools designed for the format even if not designed for the consuming system.
[src:hcl-config/configuration-file] In particular, general-purpose serialization formats, such as JSON, XML, and YAML, are often used in open-source and platform-neutral software.
[src:hcl-config/configuration-file] The specifications for these formats are generally publicly available to support wide-spread use.
[src:hcl-config/configuration-file] The following table compares notable formats used for configuration data.
[src:hcl-config/configuration-file] The *syntax typing* column indicates whether the syntax supports data types.
[src:hcl-config/configuration-file] A format has syntax-typing if a value's type is specified by syntax – e.g.
[src:hcl-config/configuration-file] `true` is a Boolean while `"true"` is a string.
[src:hcl-config/configuration-file] A format does not have syntax-typing if a value's type is based on semantics – e.g.
[src:hcl-config/configuration-file] `true` and `"true"` are both Boolean if the parser expects a Boolean.
[src:hcl-config/configuration-file] Opinions on the value of syntax-typing vary.
[src:hcl-config/configuration-file] The following are examples of config files organized by the operating systems on which they are commonly used.
[src:hcl-config/configuration-file] Many different file formats are used on Unix and Unix-like operating systems.
[src:hcl-config/configuration-file] Even so, there is a strong tradition of using human-editable, plain text formats including simple key–value pair.
[src:hcl-config/configuration-file] Filename extensions of `.cnf`, `.conf`, `.cfg`, `.cf` or `.ini` are often used.
[src:hcl-config/configuration-file] Many formats allow comments, in which case, individual settings can be disabled by prepending with the comment character.
[src:hcl-config/configuration-file] Often the default configuration files contain extensive internal documentation in the form of comments and man files are also typically used to document the format and options available.
[src:hcl-config/configuration-file] System-wide software often uses configuration files stored in `/etc`, while user applications often use a "dotfile" – a file or directory in the home directory prefixed with a period, which in Unix hides the file or directory from casual listing.
[src:hcl-config/configuration-file] Since this causes pollution, newer user applications generally make their own folder in the `.config` directory, a standardized subdirectory of the home directory.
[src:hcl-config/configuration-file] Similar to config files, a run command (rc) shell script can configure a shell session.
[src:hcl-config/configuration-file] Often, such scripts are named with an `rc` suffix after the consuming program's name such as `.xinitrc`, `.vimrc`, `.bashrc`, `xsane.rc`.
[src:hcl-config/configuration-file] By contrast, IBM's AIX uses an Object Data Manager (ODM) database to store much of its system settings.
[src:hcl-config/configuration-file] MS-DOS primarily relied on the `CONFIG.SYS` config file, a plain text file with simple key–value pairs (e.g.
[src:hcl-config/configuration-file] MS-DOS 6 introduced the INI-file format.
[src:hcl-config/configuration-file] Similar to an rc file, the batch file named `AUTOEXEC.BAT` ran commands on startup.
[src:hcl-config/configuration-file] Both these files were retained up to Windows 98SE, which still ran on top of MS-DOS.
[src:hcl-config/configuration-file] DOS applications used a wide variety of individual configuration files, most of them binary, proprietary and undocumented - and there were no common conventions or formats.
[src:hcl-config/configuration-file] Early Windows operating systems heavily utilized plain-text INI files which served as the primary mechanism to configure the operating system and applications.
[src:hcl-config/configuration-file] The APIs to read and write from these still exist in Windows, but after 1993, Microsoft began to steer developers away from using INI files and toward storing settings in the registry, a hierarchical database to store configuration settings, which was introduced with Windows NT.
[src:hcl-config/configuration-file] Later systems use XML and other formats instead of the registry.
[src:hcl-config/configuration-file] The Property List is the standard configuration file format in macOS (as well as in iOS, NeXTSTEP, GNUstep and Cocoa applications).
[src:hcl-config/configuration-file] It uses the filename extension `.plist`.
[src:hcl-config/configuration-file] IBM's OS/2 uses a binary format, also with a .INI suffix, but this differs from the Windows versions.
[src:hcl-config/configuration-file] It contains a list of lists of untyped key–value pairs.
[src:hcl-config/configuration-file] Two files control system-wide settings: OS2.INI and OS2SYS.INI.
[src:hcl-config/configuration-file] Application developers can choose whether to use them or to create a specific file for their applications.
[src:hcl-config/configuration-file] HarmonyOS and OpenHarmony-based operating systems use JSON config files, named `config.json`.
[src:hcl-config/configuration-file] The platform IDE, DevEco Studio, provides methods for editing `config.json`.
[src:hcl-config/configuration-management] CM applied over the lifecycle of a system provides visibility and control of its performance, functional, and physical attributes.
[src:hcl-config/configuration-management] CM verifies that a system performs as intended, and is documented in sufficient detail to support its projected life cycle.
[src:hcl-config/configuration-management] The CM process facilitates orderly management of system information and system changes for purposes such as to revise capability; improve performance, reliability, or maintainability; extend life; reduce costs; reduce risk and liability; or correct defects.
[src:hcl-config/configuration-management] The relatively minimal cost of implementing CM is returned manyfold in cost avoidance.
[src:hcl-config/configuration-management] The lack of CM (or its ineffectual implementation) can be very expensive and sometimes can have such catastrophic consequences such as failure of equipment or loss of life.
[src:hcl-config/configuration-management] CM emphasizes the functional relation between parts, subsystems, and systems for effectively controlling system change.
[src:hcl-config/configuration-management] It helps to verify that proposed changes are systematically considered to minimize adverse effects.
[src:hcl-config/configuration-management] Changes to the system are proposed, evaluated, and implemented using a standardized, systematic approach that ensures consistency, and proposed changes are evaluated in terms of their anticipated impact on the entire system.
[src:hcl-config/configuration-management] CM verifies that changes are carried out as specified and that documentation of items and systems reflects their true configuration.
[src:hcl-config/configuration-management] A complete CM program includes provisions for the storing, tracking, and updating of all system information on a component, subsystem, and system basis.
[src:hcl-config/configuration-management] A structured CM program ensures that documentation (e.g., requirements, design, test, and acceptance documentation) for items is accurate and consistent with the actual physical design of the item.
[src:hcl-config/configuration-management] In many cases, without CM, the documentation exists but is not consistent with the item itself.
[src:hcl-config/configuration-management] For this reason, engineers, contractors, and management are frequently forced to develop documentation reflecting the actual status of the item before they can proceed with a change.
[src:hcl-config/configuration-management] This reverse engineering process is wasteful in terms of human and other resources and can be minimized or eliminated using CM.
[src:hcl-config/configuration-management] Configuration management originated in the United States Department of Defense in the 1950s as a technical management discipline for hardware material items—and it is now a standard practice in virtually every industry.
[src:hcl-config/configuration-management] The CM process became its own technical discipline in the late 1960s when the DoD developed a series of military standards called the "480 series" (i.e., MIL-STD-480, MIL-STD-481 and MIL-STD-483) that were subsequently issued in the 1970s.
[src:hcl-config/configuration-management] This marked the beginning of what has now evolved into the most widely distributed and accepted standard on CM, ANSI–EIA–649–1998.
[src:hcl-config/configuration-management] Many of these functions and models have redefined CM from its traditional holistic approach to technical management.
[src:hcl-config/configuration-management] Some treat CM as being similar to a librarian activity and break out change control or change management as a separate or standalone discipline.
[src:hcl-config/configuration-management] CM is the practice of handling changes systematically so that a system maintains its integrity over time.
[src:hcl-config/configuration-management] CM implements the policies, procedures, techniques, and tools that manage, evaluate proposed changes, track change status, and maintain an inventory of system and support documents as the system changes.
[src:hcl-config/configuration-management] CM programs and plans provide technical and administrative direction to the development and implementation of the procedures, functions, services, tools, processes, and resources required to successfully develop and support a complex system.
[src:hcl-config/configuration-management] During system development, CM allows program management to track requirements throughout the life-cycle through acceptance and operations and maintenance.
[src:hcl-config/configuration-management] As changes inevitably occur in the requirements and design, they must be approved and documented, creating an accurate record of the system status.
[src:hcl-config/configuration-management] Ideally the CM process is applied throughout the system life cycle.
[src:hcl-config/configuration-management] Many professionals mix up or get confused with Asset management (AM, see also ISO/IEC 19770), where it inventories the assets on hand.
[src:hcl-config/configuration-management] The key difference between CM and AM is that the former does not manage the financial accounting aspect but the service that the system supports or in other words, that the latter (AM) is trying to realize value from an IT asset.
[src:hcl-config/configuration-management] The CM process for both hardware and software configuration items comprises five distinct disciplines as established in the MIL–HDBK–61A and in ANSI/EIA-649.
[src:hcl-config/configuration-management] Members of an organization interested in applying a standard change-management process will employ these disciplines as policies and procedures for establishing baselines, manage and control change, and monitor and assess the effectiveness and correctness of progress.
[src:hcl-config/configuration-management] The IEEE 12207 process IEEE 12207.2 also has these activities and adds "Release management and delivery".
[src:hcl-config/configuration-management] Configuration Identification (CI): consists of setting and maintaining baselines, which define the system or subsystem architecture, components, and any developments at any point in time.
[src:hcl-config/configuration-management] It is the basis by which changes to any part of a system are identified, documented, and later tracked through design, development, testing, and final delivery.
[src:hcl-config/configuration-management] CI incrementally establishes and maintains the definitive current basis for Configuration Status Accounting (CSA) of a system and its configuration items (CIs) throughout their life cycle (development, production, deployment, and operational support) until disposal.
[src:hcl-config/configuration-management] Configuration Control: includes the evaluation of all change-requests and change-proposals, and their subsequent approval or disapproval.
[src:hcl-config/configuration-management] It covers the process of controlling modifications to the system's design, hardware, firmware, software, and documentation.
[src:hcl-config/configuration-management] Configuration Status Accounting: includes the process of recording and reporting configuration item descriptions (e.g., hardware, software, firmware, etc.) and all departures from the baseline during design and production.
[src:hcl-config/configuration-management] In the event of suspected problems, operators can quickly verify baseline configuration and approved modifications.
[src:hcl-config/configuration-management] Configuration Verification and Audit: an independent review of hardware and software for the purpose of assessing compliance with established performance requirements, commercial and appropriate military standards, and functional, allocated, and product baselines.
[src:hcl-config/configuration-management] Configuration audits verify that the system and subsystem configuration documentation complies with the functional and physical performance characteristics before acceptance into an architectural baseline.
[src:hcl-config/configuration-management] The software configuration management (SCM) process is looked upon by practitioners as the best solution to handling changes in software projects.
[src:hcl-config/configuration-management] It identifies the functional and physical attributes of software at various points in time, and performs systematic control of changes to the identified attributes for the purpose of maintaining software integrity and traceability throughout the software development life cycle.
[src:hcl-config/configuration-management] The SCM process further defines the need to trace changes, and the ability to verify that the final delivered software has all of the planned enhancements that are supposed to be included in the release.
[src:hcl-config/configuration-management] It identifies four procedures that must be defined for each software project to ensure that a sound SCM process is implemented.
[src:hcl-config/configuration-management] These terms and definitions can change somewhat from standard to standard.
[src:hcl-config/configuration-management] ITIL specifies the use of a configuration management system (CMS) or configuration management database (CMDB) as a means of achieving industry best practices for Configuration Management.
[src:hcl-config/configuration-management] CMS helps manage a federated collection of CMDBs.
[src:hcl-config/configuration-management] The benefits of a CMS/CMDB includes being able to perform functions like root cause analysis, impact analysis, change management, and current state assessment for future state strategy development.
[src:hcl-config/configuration-management] For information assurance, CM can be defined as the management of security features and assurances through control of changes made to hardware, software, firmware, documentation, test, test fixtures, and test documentation throughout the life cycle of an information system.
[src:hcl-config/configuration-management] For example, configuration requirements may be different for a network firewall that functions as part of an organization's Internet boundary versus one that functions as an internal local network firewall.
[src:hcl-config/configuration-management] Configuration management is used to maintain an understanding of the status of complex assets with a view to maintaining the highest level of serviceability for the lowest cost.
[src:hcl-config/configuration-management] Specifically, it aims to ensure that operations are not disrupted due to the asset (or parts of the asset) overrunning limits of planned lifespan or below quality levels.
[src:hcl-config/configuration-management] In the military, this type of activity is often classed as "mission readiness", and seeks to define which assets are available and for which type of mission; a classic example is whether aircraft on board an aircraft carrier are equipped with bombs for ground support or missiles for defense.
[src:hcl-config/configuration-management] Configuration management can be used to maintain OS configuration files.
[src:hcl-config/configuration-management] Many of these systems utilize Infrastructure as Code to define and maintain configuration.
[src:hcl-config/configuration-management] The Promise theory of configuration maintenance was developed by Mark Burgess, with a practical implementation on present day computer systems in the software CFEngine able to perform real time repair as well as preventive maintenance.
[src:hcl-config/configuration-management] Understanding the "as is" state of an asset and its major components is an essential element in preventive maintenance as used in maintenance, repair, and overhaul and enterprise asset management systems.
[src:hcl-config/configuration-management] Complex assets such as aircraft, ships, industrial machinery etc. depend on many different components being serviceable.
[src:hcl-config/configuration-management] This serviceability is often defined in terms of the amount of usage the component has had since it was new, since fitted, since repaired, the amount of use it has had over its life and several other limiting factors.
[src:hcl-config/configuration-management] Understanding how near the end of their life each of these components is has been a major undertaking involving labor-intensive record keeping until recent developments in software.
[src:hcl-config/configuration-management] Many types of component use electronic sensors to capture data which provides live condition monitoring.
[src:hcl-config/configuration-management] This data is analyzed on board or at a remote location by computer to evaluate its current serviceability and increasingly its likely future state using algorithms which predict potential future failures based on previous examples of failure through field experience and modeling.
[src:hcl-config/configuration-management] This is the basis for "predictive maintenance".
[src:hcl-config/configuration-management] Availability of accurate and timely data is essential in order for CM to provide operational value and a lack of this can often be a limiting factor.
[src:hcl-config/configuration-management] Capturing and disseminating the operating data to the various support organizations is becoming an industry in itself.
[src:hcl-config/configuration-management] The consumers of this data have grown more numerous and complex with the growth of programs offered by original equipment manufacturers (OEMs).
[src:hcl-config/configuration-management] These are designed to offer operators guaranteed availability and make the picture more complex with the operator managing the asset but the OEM taking on the liability to ensure its serviceability.
[src:hcl-config/configuration-management] More recently configuration management has been applied to large construction projects which can often be very complex and have a huge number of details and changes that need to be documented.
[src:hcl-config/configuration-management] Construction agencies such as the Federal Highway Administration have used configuration management for their infrastructure projects.
[src:hcl-config/configuration-management] There are construction-based configuration management tools that aim to document change orders and RFIs in order to ensure a project stays on schedule and on budget.
[src:hcl-config/configuration-management] These programs can also store information to aid in the maintenance and modification of the infrastructure when it is completed.
[src:hcl-config/configuration-management] This study yielded results indicating a benefit to using configuration management on projects of this nature.
[src:hcl-config/declarative-programming] In computer science, **declarative programming** is a programming paradigm that expresses the logic of a computation without fully describing its control flow.
[src:hcl-config/declarative-programming] This is in contrast with imperative programming, which implements algorithms in explicit steps.
[src:hcl-config/declarative-programming] Declarative programming may consider programs as theories of a formal logic, and computations as deductions in that logical theory.
[src:hcl-config/declarative-programming] Declarative programming at times simplifies the writing of parallel programs.
[src:hcl-config/declarative-programming] Common declarative language paradigms include logic programming (e.g., Prolog, Datalog, answer set programming), and algebraic modeling systems.
[src:hcl-config/declarative-programming] Declarative programming is often defined as any style of programming that is not imperative.
[src:hcl-config/declarative-programming] A number of other common definitions attempt to define it by simply contrasting it with imperative programming.
[src:hcl-config/declarative-programming] These definitions overlap substantially.
[src:hcl-config/declarative-programming] Declarative programming is a non-imperative style of programming in which programs describe their desired results without explicitly listing commands or steps that must be performed.
[src:hcl-config/declarative-programming] Logic programming languages are characterized by a mostly declarative programming style.
[src:hcl-config/declarative-programming] In logic programming, programs consist of sentences expressed in logical form, and computation uses those sentences to solve problems, which are also expressed in logical form.
[src:hcl-config/declarative-programming] In a pure functional language, such as Haskell, all functions are without side effects, and state changes are only represented as functions that transform the state, which is explicitly represented as a first-class object in the program.
[src:hcl-config/declarative-programming] Although pure functional languages are non-imperative, they often provide a facility for describing the effect of a function as a series of steps.
[src:hcl-config/declarative-programming] Other functional languages, such as Lisp, OCaml and Erlang, support a mixture of procedural and functional programming.
[src:hcl-config/declarative-programming] Some logic programming languages, such as Prolog, and database query languages, such as SQL, while declarative in principle, also support a procedural style of programming.
[src:hcl-config/declarative-programming] Declarative programming is an umbrella term that includes a number of better-known programming paradigms.
[src:hcl-config/declarative-programming] Constraint programming states relations between variables in the form of constraints that specify the properties of the target solution.
[src:hcl-config/declarative-programming] The set of constraints is solved by giving a value to each variable so that the solution is consistent with the maximum number of constraints.
[src:hcl-config/declarative-programming] Constraint programming often complements other paradigms: functional, logical, or even imperative programming.
[src:hcl-config/declarative-programming] Makefiles, for example, specify dependencies in a declarative fashion, but include an imperative list of actions to take as well.
[src:hcl-config/declarative-programming] Similarly, yacc specifies a context free grammar declaratively, but includes code snippets from a host language, which is usually imperative (such as C).
[src:hcl-config/declarative-programming] Logic programming languages, such as Prolog, Datalog and answer set programming, compute by proving that a goal is a logical consequence of the program, or by showing that the goal is true in a model defined by the program.
[src:hcl-config/declarative-programming] Prolog computes by reducing goals to subgoals, top-down using backward reasoning, whereas most Datalog systems compute bottom-up using forward reasoning.
[src:hcl-config/declarative-programming] Answer set programs typically use SAT solvers to generate a model of the program.
[src:hcl-config/declarative-programming] Models, or mathematical representations, of physical systems may be implemented in computer code that is declarative.
[src:hcl-config/declarative-programming] The code contains a number of equations, not imperative assignments, that describe ("declare") the behavioral relationships.
[src:hcl-config/declarative-programming] When a model is expressed in this formalism, a computer is able to perform algebraic manipulations to best formulate the solution algorithm.
[src:hcl-config/declarative-programming] The mathematical causality is typically imposed at the boundaries of the physical system, while the behavioral description of the system itself is declarative or acausal.
[src:hcl-config/declarative-programming] Declarative modeling languages and environments include Analytica, Modelica and Simile.
[src:hcl-config/declarative-programming] Prolog (1972) stands for "PROgramming in LOGic." It was developed for natural language question answering, using SL resolution both to deduce answers to queries and to parse and generate natural language sentences.
[src:hcl-config/declarative-programming] The building blocks of a Prolog program are *facts* and *rules*.
[src:hcl-config/declarative-programming] Given this program, the query `eat(tom,jerry)` succeeds, while `eat(jerry,tom)` fails.
[src:hcl-config/declarative-programming] Moreover, the query `eat(X,jerry)` succeeds with the answer substitution `X=tom`.
[src:hcl-config/declarative-programming] Prolog executes programs top-down, using SLD resolution to reason backwards, reducing goals to subgoals.
[src:hcl-config/declarative-programming] In this example, it uses the last rule of the program to reduce the goal of answering the query `eat(X,jerry)` to the subgoals of first finding an X such that `big(X)` holds and then of showing that `small(jerry)` holds.
[src:hcl-config/declarative-programming] It repeatedly uses rules to further reduce subgoals to other subgoals, until it eventually succeeds in unifying all subgoals with facts in the program.
[src:hcl-config/declarative-programming] This backward reasoning, goal-reduction strategy treats rules in logic programs as procedures, and makes Prolog both a declarative and procedural programming language.
[src:hcl-config/declarative-programming] The broad range of Prolog applications is highlighted in the Year of Prolog Book, celebrating the 50 year anniversary of Prolog.
[src:hcl-config/declarative-programming] The origins of Datalog date back to the beginning of logic programming, but it was identified as a separate area around 1977.
[src:hcl-config/declarative-programming] Syntactically and semantically, it is a subset of Prolog.
[src:hcl-config/declarative-programming] But because it lacks compound terms, it is not Turing-complete.
[src:hcl-config/declarative-programming] Most Datalog systems execute programs bottom-up, using rules to reason forwards, deriving new facts from existing facts, and terminating when there are no new facts that can be derived, or when the derived facts unify with the query.
[src:hcl-config/declarative-programming] Datalog has been applied to such problems as data integration, information extraction, networking, security, cloud computing and machine learning.
[src:hcl-config/declarative-programming] Answer set programming (ASP) evolved in the late 1990s, based on the stable model (answer set) semantics of logic programming.
[src:hcl-config/declarative-programming] Like Datalog, it is a subset of Prolog; and, because it lacks compound terms, it is not Turing-complete.
[src:hcl-config/declarative-programming] Most implementations of ASP execute a program by first *grounding* the program, replacing all variables in rules by constants in all possible ways, and then using a propositional SAT solver, such as the DPLL algorithm to generate one or more models of the program.
[src:hcl-config/declarative-programming] Its applications are oriented towards solving difficult search problems and knowledge representation.
[src:hcl-config/infrastructure-as-code] The concept of managing infrastructure through code emerged from early configuration management practices.
[src:hcl-config/infrastructure-as-code] In the 1990s, tools such as CFEngine, created by Mark Burgess in 1993, introduced the idea of describing system configuration in a declarative language rather than executing manual commands, laying the intellectual groundwork for IaC.
[src:hcl-config/infrastructure-as-code] IaC emerged as organizations began managing larger and more complex infrastructure, particularly with the growth of cloud computing and the need to provision resources consistently and at scale.
[src:hcl-config/infrastructure-as-code] Treating infrastructure configuration like software - storing it in version control, reviewing it, and deploying it automatically allowed teams to reduce manual errors and reproduce environments reliably.
[src:hcl-config/infrastructure-as-code] The ability to treat infrastructure as code and use the same tools as any other software project would allow developers to rapidly deploy applications.
[src:hcl-config/infrastructure-as-code] The value of IaC can be broken down into three measurable categories: cost, speed, and risk.
[src:hcl-config/infrastructure-as-code] Cost reduction aims at helping not only the enterprise financially, but also in terms of people and effort, meaning that by removing the manual component, organizations are able to refocus their efforts on other enterprise tasks.
[src:hcl-config/infrastructure-as-code] Infrastructure automation enables speed through faster execution when configuring your infrastructure and provides visibility to help other teams across the enterprise work quickly and more efficiently.
[src:hcl-config/infrastructure-as-code] Automation removes the risk associated with human error, like manual misconfiguration; removing this can decrease downtime and increase reliability.
[src:hcl-config/infrastructure-as-code] These outcomes and attributes help the enterprise move toward implementing a culture of DevOps: the combined work of development and operations.
[src:hcl-config/infrastructure-as-code] There are generally two approaches to IaC: declarative (functional) vs. imperative (procedural).
[src:hcl-config/infrastructure-as-code] The difference between the declarative and the imperative approach is essentially *what* versus *how*.
[src:hcl-config/infrastructure-as-code] The declarative approach focuses on what the eventual target configuration should be; the imperative focuses on how the infrastructure is to be changed to meet this.
[src:hcl-config/infrastructure-as-code] The declarative approach defines the desired state and the system executes what needs to happen to achieve that desired state.
[src:hcl-config/infrastructure-as-code] Imperative defines specific commands that need to be executed in the appropriate order to end with the desired conclusion.
[src:hcl-config/infrastructure-as-code] Infrastructure as Code (IaC) allows organizations to manage servers and their configurations using code.
[src:hcl-config/infrastructure-as-code] There are two ways to apply these configurations to servers: the 'push' and 'pull' methods.
[src:hcl-config/infrastructure-as-code] In the 'push' method, the system controlling the configuration directly sends instructions to the server.
[src:hcl-config/infrastructure-as-code] In the 'pull' method, the server retrieves its own instructions from the controlling system.
[src:hcl-config/infrastructure-as-code] There are many tools that fulfill infrastructure automation capabilities and use IaC.
[src:hcl-config/infrastructure-as-code] Broadly speaking, any framework or tool that performs changes or configures infrastructure declaratively or imperatively based on a programmatic approach can be considered IaC.
[src:hcl-config/infrastructure-as-code] Traditionally, server (lifecycle) automation and configuration management tools were used to accomplish IaC.
[src:hcl-config/infrastructure-as-code] Now enterprises are also using continuous configuration automation tools or stand-alone IaC frameworks, such as Microsoft’s PowerShell DSC or AWS CloudFormation.
[src:hcl-config/infrastructure-as-code] All continuous configuration automation (CCA) tools can be thought of as extensions of traditional IaC frameworks.
[src:hcl-config/infrastructure-as-code] They leverage IaC to change, configure, and automate infrastructure, and they also provide visibility, efficiency, and flexibility in how infrastructure is managed.
[src:hcl-config/infrastructure-as-code] These additional attributes provide enterprise-level security and compliance.
[src:hcl-config/infrastructure-as-code] Community content is a key determinant of an open-source CCA tool's quality.
[src:hcl-config/infrastructure-as-code] According to Gartner, the value of CCA tools is "as dependent on user-community-contributed content and support as it is on the commercial maturity and performance of the automation tooling".
[src:hcl-config/infrastructure-as-code] Established vendors such as Puppet and Chef have created their own communities.
[src:hcl-config/infrastructure-as-code] Chef has Chef Community Repository and Puppet has PuppetForge.
[src:hcl-config/infrastructure-as-code] Other vendors rely on adjacent communities and leverage other IaC frameworks such as PowerShell DSC.
[src:hcl-config/infrastructure-as-code] New vendors are emerging that are not content-driven, but model-driven with the intelligence in the product to deliver content.
[src:hcl-config/infrastructure-as-code] These visual, object-oriented systems work well for developers, but they are especially useful to production-oriented DevOps and operations constituents that value models versus scripting for content.
[src:hcl-config/infrastructure-as-code] As the field continues to develop and change, the community-based content will become ever more important to how IaC tools are used, unless they are model-driven and object-oriented.
[src:hcl-config/infrastructure-as-code] Other tools include AWS CloudFormation, cdist, StackStorm, Juju, and Step CI.
[src:hcl-config/infrastructure-as-code] IaC can be a key attribute of enabling best practices in DevOps.
[src:hcl-config/infrastructure-as-code] Developers become more involved in defining configuration and Ops teams get involved earlier in the development process.
[src:hcl-config/infrastructure-as-code] Tools that utilize IaC bring visibility to the state and configuration of servers and ultimately provide the visibility to users within the enterprise, which brings teams together to maximize their efforts.
[src:hcl-config/infrastructure-as-code] Automation in general aims to take the confusion and error-prone aspect of manual processes and make it more efficient, and productive.
[src:hcl-config/infrastructure-as-code] Allowing for better software and applications to be created with flexibility, less downtime, and an overall cost-effective way for the company.
[src:hcl-config/infrastructure-as-code] IaC is intended to reduce the complexity that kills efficiency out of manual configuration.
[src:hcl-config/infrastructure-as-code] Automation and collaboration are considered central points in DevOps; infrastructure automation tools are often included as components of a DevOps toolchain.
[src:hcl-config/infrastructure-as-code] The 2020 Cloud Threat Report released by Unit 42 (the threat intelligence unit of cybersecurity provider Palo Alto Networks) identified around 200,000 potential vulnerabilities in infrastructure-as-code templates.
[src:hcl-config/terraform-software] Terraform was launched by HashiCorp in 2014.
[src:hcl-config/terraform-software] HashiCorp launched the Terraform Module Registry in 2017.
[src:hcl-config/terraform-software] In 2019, the paid version Terraform Enterprise was introduced.
[src:hcl-config/terraform-software] In September 2021, HashiCorp announced it would be temporarily pausing its review of community-submitted pull requests for Terraform, citing low staffing in its Terraform Core team.
[src:hcl-config/terraform-software] On August 10, 2023, HashiCorp announced that all products produced by the company would be relicensed under the Business Source License (BUSL), with HashiCorp prohibiting commercial use of the community edition by those who offer "competitive services".
[src:hcl-config/terraform-software] Terraform was previously free software available under version 2.0 of the Mozilla Public License (MPL).
[src:hcl-config/terraform-software] Joe Duffy, founder and CEO of Pulumi, criticized the announcement as "disingenuous" and said, "We tried many times to contribute upstream fixes to Terraform providers, but HashiCorp would never accept them.
[src:hcl-config/terraform-software] In August 2023, due to Terraform's relicensing, the fork OpenTF was created under the MPL.
[src:hcl-config/terraform-software] OpenTF was later renamed to OpenTofu and place under The Linux Foundation.
[src:hcl-config/terraform-software] Terraform manages external resources (such as public cloud infrastructure, private cloud infrastructure, network appliances, software as a service, and platform as a service) with "providers".
[src:hcl-config/terraform-software] HashiCorp maintains an extensive list of official providers, and can also integrate with community-developed providers.
[src:hcl-config/terraform-software] Users can interact with Terraform providers by declaring resources or by calling data sources.
[src:hcl-config/terraform-software] Rather than using imperative commands to provision resources, Terraform uses declarative configuration to describe the desired final state.
[src:hcl-config/terraform-software] Once a user invokes Terraform on a given resource, Terraform will perform CRUD actions on the user's behalf to accomplish the desired state.
[src:hcl-config/terraform-software] The infrastructure as code can be written as modules, promoting reusability and maintainability.
[src:hcl-config/terraform-software] Terraform supports a number of cloud infrastructure providers such as Amazon Web Services, Cloudflare, Microsoft Azure, IBM Cloud, Serverspace, Selectel Google Cloud Platform, Linode, DigitalOcean, Oracle Cloud Infrastructure, Yandex.Cloud, VMware vSphere, and OpenStack.
[src:hcl-config/terraform-software] It can be configured to make use of multiple cloud platforms.
[src:hcl-config/terraform-software] As of 2019, Terraform is used by companies such as Barclays, Capital One, and GM Cruise.
